// Aliased-import construction resolves to the SOURCE identity, end-to-end.
//
// `hew::aliassrc` exports a record `Payload`. The importer opts it in under the
// alias `Tag` (`import hew::aliassrc::{ Payload as Tag }`) and constructs it as
// `Tag { code: … }`. The checker resolves the bare binding `Tag` through
// `published_bare_type_qualified` to the SOURCE identity `aliassrc.Payload`
// (never a phantom `aliassrc.Tag`, which has no def) and records that qualified
// name on the construction's type.
//
// HIR lowering must stamp the source identity onto the StructInit result type,
// not the bare alias binding. If it keyed off `Tag`, the MIR field-order lookup
// would miss (the layout is registered under the bare source `Payload`, and
// `Tag` neither matches nor strips to it) and the construction would fall
// through the field-order fail-closed (`record type `Tag` not registered in
// field-order table`). With the source identity on the type, the qualified
// `aliassrc.Payload` strips to the registered bare `Payload` and both the
// construction and the subsequent field read resolve.
//
// Harness verb: hew run
// Expected: the aliased construction reads its field back as 7.
import hew::aliassrc::{ Payload as Tag };

fn main() {
    let x = Tag { code: 7 };
    let y = Tag { code: x.code + 1 };
    println(f"code={x.code} next={y.code}");
}
